Because there was a monk who asked about the essential formula of the Five Ranks of ruler and minister, the Master said: “The rank of the proper is the realm of emptiness;

originally there is not a single thing. The rank of the partial is the realm of form, with the forms of the myriad phenomena. ‘The partial within the proper’ is

turning one’s back on principle and going along with matters. ‘The proper within the partial’ is abandoning matters and entering principle. ‘The combined’ is the dark accordance

with the many conditions, not falling into the various existences—neither tainted nor pure, neither proper nor partial. Therefore it is said: the empty,

mysterious great Way, the true school without attachment. From above, the former worthies have pushed this one rank as the most subtle,

the most mysterious. One should carefully examine and discern it clearly. The ruler is the proper rank; the minister is the partial rank. The minister turning toward

the ruler is ‘the proper within the partial’. The ruler regarding the minister is ‘the partial within the proper’. The ruler and minister’s Way in accord is

the language of the combined.” The monk went on: “What is the ruler?” The Master said: “Wondrous virtue venerates the cosmos;

lofty brightness illumines the great void.” He said: “What is the minister?” The Master said: “Numinous functioning expands the sagely Way;

true wisdom benefits living beings.” He said: “What is the minister turning toward the ruler?” The Master said: “Not falling into the various

different destinies, concentrating the mind and gazing upon the holy countenance.” He said: “What is the ruler regarding the minister?” The Master said: “Wondrous

countenance, though unmoving, its light shines without partiality.” He said: “What is the ruler and minister’s Way in accord?”

The Master said: “Blended so there is no inside or outside; harmonized and fused, above and below are level.” The Master also said: “Speaking of ruler and

minister as partial and proper is because we do not wish to violate the middle; therefore the minister, in calling the ruler, does not dare to speak bluntly—

that is so. This is the essential purport of my Dharma school.” Then he composed a verse saying: “Students must first recognize their own

school; do not mix the true boundary with stubborn emptiness. When the wondrously bright substance is exhausted, it knows what is harmful and what touches;

power lies in meeting conditions without borrowing the middle. When words are uttered, directly teach that fire cannot burn it;

in hidden practice one must be in accord with the ancients. Without body yet with affairs, one transcends the divergent paths;

without affairs and without body, one falls into beginning and end.” Again he composed the five images.
